##"Go Wuhan" : Japan's hand in the epidemic | special report

Especially in the last decade, despite the ups and downs of the international situation, the economic and civil exchanges between the two countries are irreversibly sticking together, and the similar traditional cultural background makes us a contrast and a close neighbor that can hardly be cut off.
By Ren Tongyao
Editor | Luo Lixuan

In these days of anxious epidemic situation, the first friend thanked by the Chinese is Japan. From the material support, to the control plan of the epidemic, to the good will of the Japanese people to the Chinese tourists spontaneously, all have been widely spread and recognized on Chinese social media platforms.

In fact, such help has not been uncommon in recent decades. Japanese aid has been involved in SARS, the Wenchuan County earthquake, the 2010 Yushu earthquake, and so on. Especially in the last decade, despite the ups and downs of the international situation, the two countries'economic and civil exchanges are irreversibly bound together, and our similar traditional cultural background makes us a contrast and a near neighbour that can hardly be severed.

On January 26, Japanese Foreign Minister Toshiyuki Mogi held a telephone conversation with State Councilor of the People's Republic of China and Foreign Minister Wang Yi and expressed his willingness to work together with China to tackle the threat of the epidemic and provide China with all-round support and assistance. "A friend who helps in times of trouble is a friend indeed. "

Japanese aid

Since the outbreak of new-type pneumonia in Wuhan, the international community has attracted much attention. Japan confirmed its first case of COVID-19 on Jan. 15 and has since confirmed several cases. So far, the number of confirmed cases in Japan has increased to six, including one case of a bus driver who had never been to Wuhan but had twice transported group tourists there in January, according to the COVID-19.

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a "level 2 infection risk information" , asking Japanese nationals not to travel to Wuhan and Hubei provinces except in case of emergency. At the same time, all Japanese citizens in China are required to register their personal information and declare their health status at the embassies and consulates in various parts of China, and infrared temperature testing has been enhanced at the airport, put Free Disinfectant in public areas where Chinese tourists congregate.

The Japanese government has also taken a cautious approach to those infected. On Jan. 26, a news conference in Japan sparked domestic discussion, with the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare refusing to disclose the nationality of the patient when it announced the fourth case of infection. Asked by reporters, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare said: "nationality is not related to the epidemic, out of respect for the individual patient, so do not disclose nationality. "

A day later, on January 27, the Japanese government officially classified the new type of pneumonia as a "government-designated infectious disease. ". Under the Infectious Diseases Act, measures such as compulsory hospitalization can be taken against patients. At the same time, patients infected with coronavirus, regardless of nationality to implement free treatment.

"In the light of the increasing number of patients mainly in China, the government is working out relevant measures to cover the cost of hospitalization and treatment for those infected at public expense, " Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga said at a news conference this morning

In the face of a serious domestic epidemic, the Japanese government began to extend a helping hand to China. At a press conference on the morning of the 28th, in response to a question from a reporter from ifeng.com, Yoshihide Suga said once again: What can Japan do, it will do its utmost to help China. Japan will send supplies such as protective clothing and face masks."

Support operations have also been extended to specific areas. Daemun, Wuhan's first internationally friendly city, donated 30,000 masks from its disaster-prevention warehouse to Wuhan, with the words "Go Wuhan! " Written on the cardboard boxes in Chinese

The big city is in Kyushu. It's not rich. The event to mark the 40th anniversary of the founding of Wuhan and the largely friendly city on March 8 was reportedly postponed because of the outbreak. "I hope I can do something for them while keeping in close contact with Wuhan, " said Wei Tengyou, a section chief of the International Division of Culture in Dafeng City

On the 28th, the Tokyo Metropolitan Government offered to provide 20,000 sets of protective clothing for medical workers in Hubei Province. According to Phoenix reporter Li Miao, these protective clothing came from the earthquake resistant reserve in Tokyo.

Mito, a friendly city in Chongqing, donated 50,000 surgical masks to the city on Tuesday. In a letter to the mayor of Chongqing, Takahashi, the mayor of Mito, wrote: "I sincerely wish the epidemic in China an early improvement and the citizens of Chongqing an early return to a stable life! " "Go China! Go Chongqing! Go Mito! " .


Outside the official sphere, Japanese companies and individuals are reaching out to Wuhan. Japanese gaming company DMM founder Keiji Kameyama tweeted three times on January 25, saying DMM had sent a batch of medical supplies including masks and protective clothing to Wuhan, was docking with the Red Cross, and urged people to continue supporting Wuhan.


On January 26, the news that "Japan International Friends" had donated masks to China drew public attention. According to the Chinese Embassy in Japan, it was an emergency donation from a Japanese company Ito-Yokado. A total of 800,000 masks in 500 boxes were delivered to the city of Chengdu in response to the COVID-19 outbreak and have arrived in the city awaiting distribution.

Japan's Aeon Group will open five of its wuhan-based supermarkets at the government's request, leaving some of its Japanese staff behind, the Asahi Shimbun reported Thursday.

In the civil, many shops also posted in the mask area "Wuhan refueling" "China refueling" words, some shops will be discounted face masks sold, limited free distribution. Overseas Chinese in Japan also began to solicit donations.

Historical origins

Throughout history, Japan has helped China through natural disasters and epidemics. During the SARS period, Japan provided hundreds of millions of yen in funds and medical aid to China, and sent an international emergency support expert group to assist in the prevention and treatment of SARS.

During the 2008 Sichuan earthquake period and the 2010 Yushu earthquake period, Japan provided emergency free financial assistance to China. The 60-strong Japanese rescue team was the first foreign professional rescue team to arrive in the disaster area after the Wenchuan County earthquake, people from all walks of life companies, individuals have also been for the disaster area fund-raising.

Japan has provided government development assistance to the developing country since joining the Colombo Plan in 1954. After the normalization of diplomatic relations between China and Japan, Japan offered in 1979 government development assistance to China (also known as Japan's Oda  to China) to provide assistance to China through paid capital cooperation (yen loans) , unpaid capital cooperation and technical cooperation, the main funding comes from taxes paid by citizens.

Japan's prime minister at the time, Masayoshi Ōhira, said that China's modernization policy was directly related to the core issue of international coordination, and that a more prosperous China would make the world a better place, and take into account Japan's own interests before deciding to assist China.

Japan's aid to China totaled 3.65 trillion yen in 2018. Many large scale, technically difficult infrastructure projects have Japan in their sights: the construction of the Beijing Capital International Airport 2 terminal, the Shanghai Pudong International Airport, the Second Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge and other Yangtze River Bridges, the electrification of railways such as the Beijing–Qinhuangdao Railway and Nankun Railways, the construction of large berths in ports such as Qingdao Port, and the introduction of equipment by enterprises such as Wuhan Iron and Steel Group and Baoshan District Iron and Steel Group have all been assisted by low-interest and long-term loans in Japanese yen.

In addition, Japan also in health care, environmental protection, personnel education and other aspects of China's Pro Bono assistance. The sino-japanese Friendship Hospital, built in 1984, is one such achievement. The COVID-19 sent 20 medical staff to Wuhan to help with the outbreak.

From 1980 to 2018, Japan was arguably China's largest donor for 39 years. According to People's Daily Online, Japan's total assistance to China accounts for more than 60 percent of the funds of the 24 countries that provide assistance to China.

"Japan's assistance to China since 1979 has laid a foundation for China's economic construction and promoted China's economic and social development, " the State Science and Technology Commission and the Foreign Loan Administration Department of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and economic cooperation have said. In particular, gratis assistance has contributed to the development of china-japan friendship and economic and trade relations."

With the improvement of China's economic development level, the idea and discussion of gradually reducing and eventually cancelling development assistance to China also gradually emerged in Japan. After entering the 21st century, Japan has adjusted its aid policy to China several times, the ODA  has slashed its quotas for China.

In 2018, after Japan announced that it was ending its ODA  with China, foreign Ministry spokesman Hua Chunying responded, "Japan's official financial cooperation with China has played a positive role in China's reform and opening-up and economic development, and Japan has also benefited from this. ". This is an important part of the win-win cooperation between China and Japan. "

The Wuhan Epidemic, on the Japanese aid discussions and speculation a lot. In the field of online public opinion, there are many voices expressing gratitude, but also many of the aid motivation and strength of suspicion. Help from afar, however, is always appreciated, and hoots.

end
